For this mesh, we need to provide the arc's roundness info, the top ring's roundness info, and the sphere-like middle connecting part info.Â 

We use the top side of a cylinder to provide the arc's roundness info. We use 12-side cylinder so the arc would have more geo to support the round shape.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Then duplicate it aroundÂ 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Connect the middle part with bridge toolÂ 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Then we use the top side of another cylinder to provide the top ring's roundness info.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

We of course need to match the geo amount of the arc circle. The top part of the arc circle has 18 edges, so the cylinder needs 18 subdivisions to provide a matching top side.Â 

Also, we need to rotate the top side in order to find the best alignment for the geo though sometimes we might not find a perfect one.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Use bridge tool to connect them, and use extrude to build the middle hole.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Add bevel, all the bevels are standalone, so they should be fine.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Smoothed, we get a fairly good mesh.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Another way to go about building this mesh is to use boolean operation.Â 

Use a 6-side cylinder and a sphere, do a boolean subtract operation. Use the sphere to chip away the corners of the cylinder. The rest can be done through extrude and flatten faces.
